{
  "text": "In this section we present a comparative analysis of state-of-the-art of pedestrian detection. For our comparative analysis, we choose the best performing pedestrian detectors on Caltech [CITATION_1] and CityPersons [CITATION_2] . The underlying goal is to illustrate how well our baseline performs when it is fine-tune on the target dataset. We refer to the best performing baseline presented in Table 12 as Cascade R-CNN \u2020 . Table 13 shows that Cascade R-CNN \u2020 achieves 1.76 M R \u22122 on Caltech [CITATION_3] , outperforming previous best by a margin of 3.24% of M R \u22122 . This performance is approaching human-baseline (0.88) [CITATION_4] on Caltech [CITATION_5] . Moreover, we report similar improvement over the previous state-of-the-art on CityPersons [CITATION_6] benchmark. Cascade R-CNN's \u2020 performance is 3.5% M R \u22122 better than CSP [CITATION_7] . Finally, on ECP [CITATION_8] we report an improvements of 1.8% M R \u22122 over Faster R-CNN [CITATION_9] . Similar performance improvements are achieved on other subsets of all these three datasets, with the performance improvement of more than 50% for the most challenging subsets, Heavy and small. This con- ",
  "correct_citation": {
